Project positioning and how to sharpen it

Your proposed project aligns closely with emerging work on CoT‑aware attacks and defenses, but there are clear gaps you can claim.

How your idea connects to existing research
CoT‑guided adversarial prompting already boosts attack success. In Bi‑Modal Adversarial Prompt Attack (BAP) for vision–language models, an LLM uses chain‑of‑thought to analyse jailbreak failures and iteratively refine textual prompts, achieving ~+29% average increase in attack success rate over baselines 
1. This validates your idea of using CoT as a signal for adapting attacks.
CoT‑based prompt‑injection defense is emerging. Meticulous Thought Defender uses a fine‑grained CoT analysis (semantic, step/path consistency, confidence) to detect prompt injections, outperforming static rule‑based and intrinsic LLM detection by 1.16% accuracy and 3.39% F1, and by 6.24%/7.65% over intrinsic detection 5. This is a natural candidate for your “hardened defense.”
Prompt injection is recognised as a primary LLM risk. Surveys of LLM security and prompt engineering explicitly highlight prompt hacking/injection and jailbreaks as central vulnerabilities, referencing OWASP’s prompt‑hacking project as a key practical resource and stressing the need for systematic adversarial evaluation and red‑teaming style benchmarks 
3
6
